<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<recipe>
    <name>Massaman Curry with Beef (KAENG MATSAMAN NEUA)</name>
    <indexCharacter>M</indexCharacter>
    <notes></notes>
    <servings>4</servings>
    <instructions>THIS CURRY HAS MANY CHARACTERISTICS OF SOUTHERN THAI COOKING. THE SWEET FLAVOURS AND SPICES DOMINATE. EVEN THOUGH THE CURRY IS MODERATELY HOT, IT ALSO HAS A SOUR TASTE FROM THE TAMARIND. THIS DISH IS ONE OF THE FEW THAI DISHES WITH POTATOES AND PEANUTS. 

DRY-FRY the cinnamon stick, cardamom seeds and cloves in a saucepan or wok over a low heat. Stir all the ingredients around for 2 to 3 minutes or until fragrant. Remove from the pan. 

HEAT the oil in the same saucepan or wok and stir-fry the massaman paste over a medium heat for 2 minutes or until fragrant. 

ADD the beef to the pan and stir for 5 minutes. Add the coconut milk, stock, potatoes, ginger, fish sauce, palm sugar, three-quarters of the roasted peanuts, tamarind puree and the dry-fried spices. Reduce the heat to low and gently simmer for 50 to 60 minutes until the meat is tender and the potatoes are just cooked. Taste, then adjust the seasoning if necessary. Spoon into a serving bowl and garnish with the rest of the roasted peanuts.</instructions>
